h1. For AKS Users

h2. What You Need to Know

Your applications run in Kubernetes pods. To enable log shipping, you add a simple annotation to your pod configuration. That's it. OneAgent will automatically read these annotations and start shipping logs.

h2. Enable Log Shipping

Add these lines to your deployment metadata. Replace the paths with your actual log file locations.

{code:language=yaml}
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
  namespace: my-namespace
spec:
  template:
    metadata:
      annotations:
        dynatrace.com/log-shipping: "true"
        dynatrace.com/log-paths: |
          /var/log/app/application.log
          /var/log/app/error.log
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-app
        image: my-image:latest
{code}

h2. Optional Settings

If you want more control, you can add these optional annotations:

{code:language=yaml}
# Send only error and warning logs (reduces volume)
dynatrace.com/log-level: "WARN,ERROR"

# Specify log format for better parsing
dynatrace.com/log-format: "json"

# Add custom labels for organization
dynatrace.com/log-labels: "team=backend,service=payments,env=prod"
{code}

h2. What Happens Next

After you apply your deployment, give it about 5 minutes. Then go into Dynatrace and look at the Logs section. You should see your application logs appear. If they don't show up, see the troubleshooting section below.

h2. Disable Log Shipping

Just remove the annotations from your deployment and redeploy. Logs will stop appearing within 5 minutes.

