h1. For Linux VM Users

h2. What You Need to Know

On Linux VMs, we use a folder-based approach. You create symlinks from your log files to a special monitoring directory. OneAgent automatically picks up anything in that directory.

h2. Directory Structure

We've created this structure on your VMs:

{code}
/opt/dynatrace/logshipping/
├── platform/              <- Platform logs (always monitored)
│   ├── kernel/
│   ├── audit/
│   └── system/
└── applications/          <- Your application logs (opt-in)
    ├── my-app/
    └── other-app/
{code}

h2. Enable Log Shipping

Open a terminal and run these commands. Replace "my-app" with your application name and update the paths to match your log locations.

{code:language=bash}
# Step 1: Create a directory for your application
mkdir -p /opt/dynatrace/logshipping/applications/my-app

# Step 2: Create symlinks to your log files
ln -s /var/log/my-app/application.log /opt/dynatrace/logshipping/applications/my-app/app.log
ln -s /var/log/my-app/error.log /opt/dynatrace/logshipping/applications/my-app/error.log

# Step 3: Verify it worked
ls -la /opt/dynatrace/logshipping/applications/my-app/
{code}

h2. What Happens Next

OneAgent checks this directory every few minutes. Within 5 minutes, your logs should appear in Dynatrace. Go to the Logs section and search for your application name.

h2. Disable Log Shipping

When you no longer need logs in Dynatrace:

{code:language=bash}
rm -rf /opt/dynatrace/logshipping/applications/my-app
{code}

That's it. Logs will stop appearing within 5 minutes.

