h1. For Windows VM Users

h2. What You Need to Know

On Windows VMs, we use a folder-based approach. You copy your log files to a special monitoring directory. OneAgent automatically picks up anything new in that directory.

h2. Directory Structure

We've created this structure on your VMs:

{code}
C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\
├── Platform\              <- Platform logs (always monitored)
│   ├── System\
│   ├── Security\
│   └── Application\
└── Applications\          <- Your application logs (opt-in)
    ├── MyApp\
    └── OtherApp\
{code}

h2. Enable Log Shipping

Open PowerShell and run these commands. Replace "MyApp" with your application name and update the paths to match your log locations.

{code:language=powershell}
# Step 1: Create a directory for your application
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\Applications\MyApp" -Force

# Step 2: Copy your log files
Copy-Item -Path "C:\Logs\MyApp\*.log" -Destination "C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\Applications\MyApp\"

# Step 3: Verify it worked
Get-ChildItem -Path "C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\Applications\MyApp\"
{code}

h2. What Happens Next

OneAgent checks this directory every few minutes. Within 5 minutes, your logs should appear in Dynatrace. Go to the Logs section and search for your application name.

h2. Continuous Updates (Optional)

If you want your logs to stay up-to-date automatically, you can set up a scheduled task to copy new logs:

{code:language=powershell}
# This creates a task that copies logs every 5 minutes
$taskName = "Dynatrace-MyApp-LogSync"
$action = New-ScheduledTaskAction -Execute "robocopy" -Argument 'C:\Logs\MyApp C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\Applications\MyApp /MIR'
$trigger = New-ScheduledTaskTrigger -RepetitionInterval (New-TimeSpan -Minutes 5) -Once -At (Get-Date)
Register-ScheduledTask -TaskName $taskName -Action $action -Trigger $trigger -RunLevel Highest
Start-ScheduledTask -TaskName $taskName
{code}

h2. Disable Log Shipping

When you no longer need logs in Dynatrace:

{code:language=powershell}
Remove-Item -Path "C:\Dynatrace\LogShipping\Applications\MyApp" -Recurse -Force
{code}

That's it. Logs will stop appearing within 5 minutes.

